docs.abstract: The singer Crush apologized for a “misunderstanding” after the exchange, which highlights what experts call K-pop’s uneasy relationship with Black culture.
docs.snippet: The singer Crush apologized for a “misunderstanding” after the exchange, which highlights what experts call K-pop’s uneasy relationship with Black culture.
docs.lead_paragraph: It happens so fast in the videos that you need to rewatch them to notice: As Crush, a South Korean R&B singer, high-fives fans during a recent performance, he avoids an area where some Black concertgoers have extended their hands.

headline.main: A K-Pop Star Didn’t High-Five Black Fans. Was It Racism?
headline.print_headline: K-Pop Star Ignites Controversy by Not High-Fiving Black Fans

docs.abstract: This weekend’s broadcast, hosted by Simu Liu, also included some helpful Thanksgiving tips and, uh, Dog Head Man.

docs.lead_paragraph: About a half-hour into this weekend’s broadcast, “Saturday Night Live” would devote an entire sketch to a character with a dog’s head and neck attached to a human body. But first, the show addressed the acquittal of Kyle Rittenhouse.

docs.abstract: Mr. Hill, 47, was fatally shot by a police officer in December while he was in a garage. An agreement announced on Friday paves the way for the city’s largest settlement.
docs.snippet: Mr. Hill, 47, was fatally shot by a police officer in December while he was in a garage. An agreement announced on Friday paves the way for the city’s largest settlement.
docs.lead_paragraph: City officials in Columbus, Ohio, have agreed to pay a $10 million settlement to the family of Andre Hill, a Black man who was fatally shot by a police officer in a garage in December.

headline.main: Andre Hill’s Family Reaches $10 Million Settlement With City of Columbus

docs.abstract: The critical crossfire Ms. Gu has faced has implications that go far beyond the Olympic slopes, Chinese Americans say. And some see themselves in the duality she has embraced.

docs.abstract: DETROIT — Holly Lambert, part of a thinning crowd in front of the TCF Center in Detroit, has been anxiously awaiting the outcome of the presidential election. She said on Friday that she believed her freedoms were at stake if Joseph R. Biden Jr. were declared the winner.
docs.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — Holly Lambert, part of a thinning crowd in front of the TCF Center in Detroit, has been anxiously awaiting the outcome of the presidential election. She said on Friday that she believed her freedoms were at stake if Joseph R. Biden Jr. were declared the winner.

headline.main: ‘I stay up all night waiting and praying,’ says one protester in Detroit.
